<HEADLINE>
<P>
GORBACHEV A WIMP? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Probably the last Russian leader who had to put up with press attacks while 
still in office was Aleksandr F. Kerensky, prime minister in the provisional 
government that briefly held power in 1917 between the overthrow of the Romanov 
dynasty and the Bolshevik coup d'etat. Not coincidentally, Kerensky was also 
the last -- in fact, the only -- Russian leader chosen by democratic vote. 
Democracy, in the basic sense of allowing a free choice among parties and 
candidates, still isn't on the Soviet agenda. But the taboo that has always 
insulated the Soviet Union's highest official from domestic press criticism has 
at least been set aside, if only temporarily. Mikhail S. Gorbachev now finds 
himself accused of a certain wimpishness for failing to do enough to bring 
about the reforms that he has been championing for four years. 
</P>
<P>
The attack in the political and literary monthly Neva was written by Sergei Y. 
Andreyev, a young scientist working in western Siberia. Perestroika, he writes, 
seems doomed to fail, given the opposition of the "new class" of bureaucrats in 
industry, government and the Communist Party that ignores the interests of the 
public even as it moves the country to "economic crisis and moral decline." 
What's needed, Andreyev says, is a system under which independent unions and 
political organizations can develop to provide a countervailing force to the 
party's monopoly on power. All this stops short of a demand for a multiparty 
political system, but the direction of Andreyev's thinking is clear. 
</P>
<P>
The significance of the Neva article is that it seems to give semi-official 
status to what dissident intellectuals and other radical reformers have for 
some time been saying in less visible forums. These people support perestroika; 
what they fear is that its slow progress in the face of an eroding standard of 
living threatens its collapse, and they believe that this can be avoided only 
if the pace of change is drastically quickened. What should be made of the 
attack on Gorbachev himself? Perhaps very little. This would not, after all, be 
the first time he has used the public exposure of major grievances to support 
his efforts to speed reform. What bears watching now is whether the Andreyev 
article will prove a one-time thing or whether it will be taken as a sign that 
further and even more pointed public debate may now take place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Editorial 
</P>
