<HEADLINE>
<P>
HUNGARIAN REFORMER'S VIEW ON 1956 REVOLT APPARENTLY REJECTED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BUDAPEST, Hungary 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Communist Party spokesman indicated Saturday that party leaders have rejected 
a Politburo reformer's reassessment of the 1956 revolt as a popular uprising. 
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Emil Kimmel told Hungarian Radio that speakers at a crucial Friday 
session of the 108-member Central Committee said there should be no 
"single-word summary formulations" to reassess the past. 
</P>
<P>
Politburo member Imre Pozsgay startled the nation Jan. 28 by saying the 1956 
rebellion against Soviet control was "a popular uprising." Officially, it was 
called a counterrevolution. 
</P>
<P>
The meeting resumed Saturday with the media reporting few specifics. 
</P>
<P>
Pozsgay said his assessment was based on findings of a Hungarian Communist 
Party commission investigating four decades of Communist rule in Hungary. 
</P>
<P>
Prominent Central Committee member Gyula Horn, also state secretary at the 
Foreign Ministry, hinted late Friday that Pozsgay's stance was not accepted by 
most members. 
</P>
<P>
Varying only slightly from the official stance, Horn said on television that 
the meeting's "very careful assessment" showed the revolt "started as an 
uprising, some may call it a 'popular uprising,' but later on it turned into 
something which could be termed a counterrevolution." 
</P>
<P>
State media displayed none of their new openness in reporting on Friday's 
closed-door session. It was not known what was said by Pozsgay and other senior 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
According to Kimmel, the speakers supported the basic idea expounded in a 
report submitted by Communist Party chief Karoly Grosz, which says "one can 
establish order without a reform, but the reform may not be instituted without 
order." 
</P>
<P>
He also said Grosz called for an action program for the future. Grosz's speech 
has not been published and no other details were disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
Communist Party spokesman indicated Saturday that party leaders have rejected a 
Politburo reformer's reassessment of the 1956 revolt as a popular uprising. 
</P>
</TEXT>
